  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Elegy for Gu Ryeongseong
  author: Shin Sukju
  language: eng
  text: |-
    One breath gathers and scatters—
    Death and life like day and night.
    Heaven's way has always been so;
    Why grieve with empty sighs?

    This truth I knew from the start,
    Yet cannot cast it from my mind.
    You were my teacher, my guide—
    Your virtue matched the very cosmos.
    Wide as ten thousand fathoms of water,
    Who could measure your depths?

    Blessed by heaven, you served the bright age,
    A pillar and foundation of the great hall.
    Tongues wagged with idle criticism,
    Yet found no flaw in you.
    Virtue brings long life, they say;
    What is sown must surely be reaped—
    I thought you'd live a hundred years.
    Then suddenly this calamity struck.

    Fifty years we walked together,
    Our robes hem to hem, our carriages side by side.
    Yet who can trust in human affairs?
    In one evening, you vanished.

    Memory burns—the past returns.
    Two streams of tears fall.
    The city churns with wind and rain;
    By a solitary lamp I write the mourning ode.
    The fifth watch sounds clear,
    And I sit alone, unable to sleep.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Gu Ryeongseong (구릉성) likely refers to a location or symbolic place associated with the deceased.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'mourning ode' (초혼사) references the shamanic practice of calling back the spirit of the deceased.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'fifth watch' (오경) marks the last hour before dawn, traditionally a time of deepest grief and loneliness.
